    shopkeeper: [`The moment the word came down the street I put the good tea on and unlocked the door and set out the tiny socks I've been saving since autumn — smaller than two fingers, first pair free, always. A new customer arrived in town today. Youngest one I've ever stocked for. I'll be keeping her shelf full for the next forty years. Best inventory I'll ever carry.`],
    trainer: [`STRONG LUNGS! Did you HEAR those lungs?! That's a NATURAL ATHLETE, that's PERFECT FORM on the very first cry, that's a CHAMPION'S FIRST BREATH! I stood ready to carry ANYONE and instead I just stood in the hall and WEPT with PRIDE! The newest member of the town and she's already got the best form I've ever heard! I'm making a pamphlet! IT'S JUST HER NAME AND A HEART!`],
    boss: [`I cleared my whole week for this and I've never spent a week better. I stood in a hallway at dawn with the entire town and heard a new person announce herself to the world, and every deal I ever closed went quiet and small next to it. That's the only acquisition that ever mattered: the town, acquiring one more heart to love. Best morning on the books. The books are closed. Go be with your family.`],
    coworker: [`@7 The folder labeled SPRING, open since autumn, finally got its title entry, written with a hand I couldn't keep steady: "She's born. Sunrise. Both healthy. Loud. Perfect." And Gerald — Gerald shed his seventh leaf at the exact moment we heard the cry, leaf seven for milestone seven, and it dropped into the one empty slot left in the display case, the slot I always somehow knew was waiting for spring. The set's complete now. Seven leaves. Seven milestones. One town. One new heart. The archive's full. The archive's PERFECT.`],
    oldman: [`@7 I carried the first warm roll up those clinic steps slow as syrup, grandson, spoken for since autumn by grandpa's own orders, and I laid it on her blanket and felt her tiny chest rise and fall under my old hand. Sixty-two years I've fed this town, and every single loaf was practice for this one — the first bread of a brand new life. There's a person here who wasn't here yesterday. I got to be alive to feed her. What did I ever do to deserve a morning this good. Nothing. You don't earn mornings like this. You just get to be lucky enough to see one. And I did. I DID.`],
    cat: [`The little gray marshal kept the clinic step through the whole long night and into the dawn, facing out, on watch over the gathered town while the newest heart arrived behind the door it guarded. When the first cry came, it did not startle — it simply rose, walked one slow lap of the clinic, checked every corner the way it was taught, and returned to its post, satisfied: the town was safe, and larger now by one. Later, when they carried the baby home, it fell in beside the family, three paces behind, already on duty for the smallest citizen it would ever guard. The old marshal had trained it for exactly this. He'd known she was coming. He'd made sure she'd be watched over. And she would be — every day of her life, by a marshal who never met her teacher's teacher, in a town where the watch is never, ever dropped.`],
    grandma: [`@6 I ran out of words twice in my whole long life, dear — once when my husband finally came back to me, and once just now, when this tiny new person gripped my finger and looked at me like she'd been expecting me all along. I knitted for her for a year, every stitch a question. And there's the answer, warm and furious and holding on tight. Hello, little one. I've been saving up a whole lifetime of stories just for you. We'll start them soon. Final. …The softest final yet. Softer even than the snow.`],
    tmother: [`I planned nothing and witnessed everything, which I have finally learned is the higher art. A granddaughter, born at sunrise, wrapped in a quilt the whole town sewed. There was nothing to organize — grief and joy and a whole valley's love arranged themselves perfectly without a single binder, the way the truest things always do. I held the tea tray in the hallway and I wept and I was PRESENT. Tab twelve. The only tab. Witness. I passed the final exam. She's here.`],
    tfather: [`@2 SHE'S HERE, SON! MY GRANDDAUGHTER IS HERE! I waited ALL WINTER as a distant respectful boat and the SECOND I heard that first furious cry I made the LOUDEST, PROUDEST, most JOYFUL BOAT SOUND THIS VALLEY HAS EVER KNOWN — a boat home from the longest voyage with the greatest treasure aboard — and Mori did not even tell me to lower it, she just WEPT, and a weeping Mori is the highest honor there IS! SIX TOWELS! I USED ALL SIX! AND I'D USE SIXTY MORE! MY GRANDDAUGHTER! BORN AT SUNRISE! IN THE BEST TOWN ON EARTH!`],
    kenji: [`@1 I've delivered a thousand babies and kept my hands steady through every one — and this morning, for a friend's daughter, in the town that gave me a home, my voice cracked clean in half on the word "perfect," and I didn't try to fix it. Some professionalism you're glad to lose. She's healthy, she's strong, she's early and furious and absolutely fine. Best delivery of my career, and it's not close. I got to catch the town's next heart at sunrise. Nothing tops that. Nothing ever will. I'm so glad I'm this town's doctor. So glad.`],
    mori: [`@2 I have attended ten thousand births and wept at none, because a surgeon's tears help no one and I had trained mine into silence forty years ago. This morning they came anyway — quiet, unbidden, entirely against policy — at the first cry of a child I helped arrive into the one place that taught me a heart is for more than pumping. Excellent lungs. Textbook. Perfect. And I cried, and I let myself, and I will not be revising the policy back. Note it. Then let me keep it. …Welcome, little one. You have been born into a very, very good town. I would know. It saved me too. Final.`],
    hanabi: [`@7 She's HERE — and the big firework's loaded by the pond, the brightest one I've ever built, blank in the very center where a name will go the instant they choose one. I make things that shine for eight seconds and let go; this town makes a person who'll shine for eighty years and stay. The loud one's holding my hand and neither of us can talk, just crying and grinning at the clinic window with the sunrise behind it. Give her a name. Give her a name and I will paint it across this whole valley in light so bright the koi look up. I've been waiting all winter to make some noise. Let me make it for her.`]
